faq:
  - q: "What are the five elements in Chinese philosophy?"
    a: "The five elements (Wu Xing) are Wood, Fire, Earth, Metal, and Water. They represent dynamic phases of transformation, not static substances, and describe how energy moves and changes throughout the universe."
  - q: "What is the generating cycle?"
    a: "The generating cycle (相生): Wood feeds Fire, Fire creates Earth, Earth bears Metal, Metal collects Water, Water nourishes Wood. Each element nurtures the next in a productive 'mother-child' relationship."
  - q: "How do elements relate to the zodiac?"
    a: "Each zodiac year combines an animal with an element through the Heavenly Stems. This creates 60 unique year types in the sexagenary cycle (12 animals x 5 elements). The element modifies the animal's character — a Water Rat differs significantly from a Fire Rat."
  - q: "Is Wu Xing the same as Western classical elements?"
    a: "No. Western elements (earth, water, air, fire) were conceived as fundamental building-block substances. Wu Xing are dynamic phases — processes rather than materials — embedded in cyclical relationships. The Chinese system has no 'air' element; Metal and Wood have no Western equivalents."
  - q: "How are the five elements used in Chinese medicine?"
    a: "Each element maps to organ pairs, emotions, tastes, seasons, and body tissues. This framework from the Huangdi Neijing guides diagnosis: a liver condition (Wood) might be treated by strengthening its mother (Water) or calming its controller (Metal)."
