    <section id="generating">
      <h2>The Generating Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">相生</span>)</h2>
      <p>Each element nourishes and gives rise to the next in a continuous cycle of creation &mdash; the "mother-child" relationship:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wood feeds Fire</strong> &mdash; wood burns to create flame</li>
        <li><strong>Fire creates Earth</strong> &mdash; fire produces ash, which becomes soil</li>
        <li><strong>Earth bears Metal</strong> &mdash; minerals and ores form within the earth</li>
        <li><strong>Metal collects Water</strong> &mdash; metal surfaces condense moisture</li>
        <li><strong>Water nourishes Wood</strong> &mdash; water is essential for plant growth</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="overcoming">
      <h2>The Overcoming Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">相克</span>)</h2>
      <p>Each element restrains and controls another, maintaining balance through regulation:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wood penetrates Earth</strong> &mdash; roots break through soil</li>
        <li><strong>Earth dams Water</strong> &mdash; levees contain floods</li>
        <li><strong>Water extinguishes Fire</strong> &mdash; water quenches flame</li>
        <li><strong>Fire melts Metal</strong> &mdash; the forge transforms ore</li>
        <li><strong>Metal chops Wood</strong> &mdash; the axe fells the tree</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Both cycles are essential. Without the generating cycle, nothing would grow. Without the overcoming cycle, growth would be unchecked. Together they model the dynamic equilibrium that governs all natural systems.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="medicine">
      <h2>Wu Xing in Chinese Medicine</h2>
      <div class="callout-box callout-box--jade">
